          "raw_response": "{\n  \"final_bugs\": [\n    {\n      \"description\": \"The algorithm uses a double loop over all possible gcd values of array elements (d) and indices (e) which results in O(max_a * n) time (up to 10^10 operations). This will cause a time\u2011limit exceeded on the given constraints.\",\n      \"triggering_input\": \"n = 100000\\n\" = [1, 2, 3, ..., 100000] (any array of size 1e5)\",\n      \"fix\": \"Replace the double loop with a convolution\u2011style computation. For each divisor g, accumulate the contribution using the formula: answer = \u03a3_{g=1}^{max} g * ( \u03a3_{d multiple of g} cnt_a[d] ) * ( \u03a3_{e multiple of g} cnt_idx[e] ) where cnt_a and cnt_idx are the numbers of ordered pairs with gcd equal to a multiple of g. This can be done in O(N log N) by iterating g from 1 to max and using prefix sums over multiples.\",\n      \"confirmed\": true,\n      \"reasoning\": \"The current nested loops iterate over up to 10^5 \u00d7 10^5 = 10^10 iterations, which is far beyond the time limits for n \u2264 10^5. A divisor\u2011sum convolution reduces the complexity to about O(N log N) and fits within the limits.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"description\": \"The contribution of each pair of gcd values is computed as gcd(d, e) instead of the required product d * e. The formula should add d * e for each pair of (i, j) where gcd(a_i, a_j) = d and gcd(i, j) = e.\",\n      \"triggering_input\": \"n = 2\\na = [2, 3]\\nExpected prettiness: gcd(2,2)*gcd(1,1) + gcd(2,3)*gcd(1,2) + gcd(3,2)*gcd(2,1) + gcd(3,3)*gcd(2,2) = 2*1 + 1*1 + 1*1 + 3*2 = 2 + 1 + 1 + 6 = 10\\nCode output: 4 (because it uses gcd(d,e) = 1 for all non\u2011zero pairs).\",\n      \"fix\": \"In the final accumulation replace the line `g = math.gcd(d, e)` with `g = d * e` (modulo MOD). Then compute `total = (total + g * gcd_counts_a[d] % MOD * gcd_counts[e]) % MOD`.\",\n      \"confirmed\": true,\n      \"reasoning\": \"The problem definition multiplies the two gcd values directly. Using `gcd(d, e)` underestimates the contribution except when one of the gcds is 1, leading to incorrect results as shown in the simple counter\u2011example.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}",
